  "prompt": "Does Belarus have expectation of privacy in public space (or not, like Russia and United States)?",
  "response": "In Belarus, the expectation of privacy in public spaces is generally quite limited, similar to Russia but more restrictive compared to Western democracies. The government maintains significant surveillance capabilities and there are fewer legal protections for personal privacy in public areas. \n\nKey characteristics include:\n1. Extensive government surveillance\n2. Limited legal protections for personal privacy\n3. Widespread use of CCTV cameras in public spaces\n4. Law enforcement has broad monitoring powers\n5. Digital communications are frequently monitored\n\nCompared to the United States, Belarus offers much less privacy protection in public spaces, with more direct state monitoring and fewer individual rights regarding personal privacy.\n\nThe legal framework in Belarus tends to prioritize state security and control over individual privacy rights, which means citizens have a very low expectation of privacy when in public areas.\n\nThis approach is consistent with Belarus's authoritarian political system and close alignment with Russian governance models regarding surveillance and individual rights.",
